            The real
complaint against developing <ENAMEX TYPE="GPE_DESC">countries</ENAMEX> is not that their exports are based on
low wages and sweatshops. The complaint is that they export at all. And so the
supposed <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">friends</ENAMEX> of poor <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">workers</ENAMEX> abroad are no <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">friends</ENAMEX> at all. If they got
their way the result for the poor <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Freedonian</ENAMEX> would not just be no sweatshop--it
would be no job. And manufactured exports, initially based on low wages, are
the only route we know for rapid economic development.

            As I pointed out in an earlier column in

                  Slate
               , the growth of labor-intensive exports from Third World
<ENAMEX TYPE="GPE_DESC">countries</ENAMEX>, a development possible only because those <ENAMEX TYPE="GPE_DESC">countries</ENAMEX> are able to
offset their disadvantages by competing on the basis of cheap labor, has
brought about a huge improvement in the human condition, even if the wages look
miserably low by our standards.

            It is hard to believe that
<ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">people</ENAMEX> who have spent <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">years</TIMEX>, even <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">decades</TIMEX>, writing about economics are really
so fuzzy-minded that they cannot see the difference between protecting
<ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">consumers</ENAMEX> from tainted <ENAMEX TYPE="SUBSTANCE">produce</ENAMEX> and protecting <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">workers</ENAMEX> from competing products.
On the other hand, I doubt that they are purely cynical. It is more likely that
some kind of double-think, some convenient ability to stop thinking clearly
when the situation demands it, is at work. But the truth is that I don't
